# HTML Attributes Reference

This is a reference guide for commonly used HTML attributes along with their descriptions and example usage.

## Basic Attributes

1. **id**:
   - Uniquely identifies an element, useful for targeting with CSS or JavaScript.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <div id="uniqueId">This is a div with unique ID</div>
     ```

2. **class**:
   - Assigns one or more CSS classes to an element, for styling or JavaScript purposes.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <div class="box red">Red Box</div>
     ```

3. **src**:
   - Specifies the URL of the image, audio, video, or script file to be embedded.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <img src="image.jpg" alt="Image">
     ```

4. **href**:
   - Specifies the URL of the page the link goes to.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <a href="https://www.example.com">Visit Example</a>
     ```

5. **alt**:
   - Provides alternative text for images, displayed when the image cannot be loaded or for accessibility.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">
     ```

## Visual Attributes

6. **style**:
   - Defines inline CSS styles for an element.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <div style="color: blue; font-size: 18px;">Styled Text</div>
     ```

7. **title**:
   - Provides additional information about an element, often displayed as a tooltip.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <span title="This is additional information">Hover over me</span>
     ```
it didn't work in my case

8. **target**:
   - Specifies where to open the linked document.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <a href="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a>
     ```

9. **rel**:
   - Specifies the relationship between the current document and the linked document.
   - Example:
     ```html
     <a href="stylesheet.css" rel="stylesheet">External Stylesheet</a>
     ```

10. **type**:
    - Specifies the media type of the linked document.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <link href="stylesheet.css" type="text/css" rel="stylesheet">
      ```

## Form Attributes

11. **value**:
    - Specifies the value of an input element.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" value="Default Value">
      ```

12. **name**:
    - Specifies the name of an element, used when submitting form data.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" name="username">
      ```

13. **disabled**:
    - Disables an input element or a group of elements.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <button disabled>Disabled Button</button>
      ```

14. **checked**:
    - Specifies whether a checkbox or radio button should be checked by default.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="checkbox" checked>
      ```

15. **placeholder**:
    - Provides a hint or example text for input fields.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" placeholder="Enter your email">
      ```

## Additional Attributes

16. **srcset**:
    - Specifies multiple versions of an image for different display resolutions.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <img srcset="image-320.jpg 320w, image-480.jpg 480w, image-800.jpg 800w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 480px, 800px" src="image.jpg" alt="Responsive Image">
      ```

17. **download**:
    - Specifies that the target will be downloaded when a user clicks on the hyperlink.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <a href="file.pdf" download>Download PDF</a>
      ```

18. **required**:
    - Specifies that an input field must be filled out before submitting the form.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" required>
      ```

19. **colspan**:
    - Specifies the number of columns a cell should span in a table.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <td colspan="2">Spanning two columns</td>
      ```

20. **rowspan**:
    - Specifies the number of rows a cell should span in a table.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <td rowspan="2">Spanning two rows</td>
      ```

## Accessibility Attributes

21. **lang**:
    - Specifies the language of the element's content for internationalization.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <p lang="en">English text</p>
      ```

22. **max**:
    - Specifies the maximum value for an input field.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="number" max="100">
      ```

23. **min**:
    - Specifies the minimum value for an input field.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="number" min="0">
      ```

24. **step**:
    - Specifies the increment or decrement for an input field.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="number" step="0.5">
      ```

25. **selected**:
    - Specifies that an option in a dropdown menu should be pre-selected when the page loads.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <select>
        <option value="1">Option 1</option>
        <option value="2" selected>Option 2</option>
        <option value="3">Option 3</option>
      </select>
      ```

26. **readonly**:
    - Specifies that an input field is read-only and cannot be modified.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" value="Read-only text" readonly>
      ```

27. **autofocus**:
    - Specifies that an input field should automatically get focus when the page loads.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" autofocus>
      ```

28. **hidden**:
    - Specifies that an element is not yet, or is no longer, relevant.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <div hidden>This content is hidden</div>
      ```

29. **for**:
    - Specifies which form element a label is bound to.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <label for="username">Username:</label>
      <input type="text" id="username" name="username">
      ```

30. **defer**:
    - Specifies that the script execution should be deferred until after the document is parsed.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <script src="script.js" defer></script>
      ```

## Extra Attributes

31. **aria-label**:
    - Provides an accessible label for elements that do not have visible text content.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <button aria-label="Close">X</button>
      ```

32. **dir**:
    - Specifies the direction of text within an element, such as left-to-right (`"ltr"`) or right-to-left (`"rtl"`).
    - Example:
      ```html
      <div dir="rtl">مرحبا بالعالم</div>
      ```

33. **tabindex**:
    - Specifies the order in which elements receive focus when navigating using the keyboard.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" tabindex="1">
      <input type="text" tabindex="2">
      ```

34. **autocomplete**:
    - Specifies whether form autofill should be enabled or disabled for an input field.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" autocomplete="off">
      ```

35. **role**:
    - Specifies the semantic role of an element for accessibility purposes.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <div role="button" onclick="alert('Button clicked')">Click me</div>
      ```

36. **data-**:
    - Allows you to store custom data attributes on an element.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <div data-custom="value">Custom data attribute</div>
      ```

37. **list**:
    - Associates an input field with a datalist element to provide autocompletion suggestions.
    - Example:
      ```html
      <input type="text" list="options">
      <datalist id="options">
        <option value="Option 1">
        <option value="Option 2">
        <option value="Option 3">
        <option value="Option 4">
      </datalist>
      ```



